# Sendline production bring-up checklist

Why there are two nginx configs:

1. sendline-bootstrap.conf
- Use this first, before any certificate exists.
- It only needs plain HTTP on port 80.
- Its job is to serve /.well-known/acme-challenge/ from /var/www/certbot and proxy the app on HTTP.
- Use it to verify that the ACME challenge file is reachable from the public internet.

2. sendline-tls.conf
- Use this only after certbot has already created:
	- /etc/letsencrypt/live/<domain>/fullchain.pem
	- /etc/letsencrypt/live/<domain>/privkey.pem
- It keeps the HTTP challenge path available on port 80 and enables HTTPS on 443.
- This repo's TLS config is self-contained and does not require Certbot's nginx helper snippets.

Reason for the split:
- nginx cannot load a TLS server block if the certificate files do not exist yet.
- The safest flow is bootstrap first, certbot second, TLS third.

Fresh Oracle Cloud instance checklist:

1. Public networking
- Confirm the instance has the expected public IPv4.
- Point the domain A record to that public IPv4.
- If you use Cloudflare, keep the record DNS-only until HTTP-01 finishes.

2. OCI ingress rules
- Open TCP 22 from your management IP or a narrow CIDR.
- Open TCP 80 from 0.0.0.0/0.
- Open TCP 443 from 0.0.0.0/0.
- Check both Security List and NSG if the instance uses both.

3. Host firewall
- Do not assume "ufw not installed" means "no firewall".
- Check active rules:
	- sudo nft list ruleset
	- sudo iptables -L INPUT -n -v
- If the INPUT chain only allows 22 and rejects everything else, allow 80 and 443 explicitly.

Example fix when iptables-nft is managing the active rules:

sudo iptables -I INPUT 5 -p tcp --dport 80 -m conntrack --ctstate NEW -j ACCEPT
sudo iptables -I INPUT 6 -p tcp --dport 443 -m conntrack --ctstate NEW -j ACCEPT

4. Base packages
- Install nginx.
- Install certbot.
- Install Docker only if the app will run in containers.
- Install mysql client tools if you want direct DB health checks.

5. App runtime prerequisites
- Confirm the app listens on the expected local port, usually 127.0.0.1:8080 or 0.0.0.0:8080.
- Confirm DB_HOST, DB_PORT, DB_USER, DB_PASSWORD, and DB_NAME are correct.
- If PUBLIC_BASE_URL is set, it must include the scheme, for example:
	- https://sendline.cachigo.com
- If BASE_PATH is empty, leave it truly empty. Do not set "/".

6. Bootstrap nginx phase
- Copy only sendline-bootstrap.conf into /etc/nginx/conf.d/sendline.conf.
- Create the certbot webroot:
	- sudo mkdir -p /var/www/certbot/.well-known/acme-challenge
- Put a manual test file there:
	- echo ok | sudo tee /var/www/certbot/.well-known/acme-challenge/test-file
- Validate nginx:
	- sudo nginx -t
	- sudo systemctl restart nginx

7. Verify the challenge path before certbot
- Local host check:
	- curl -i -H 'Host: <domain>' http://127.0.0.1/.well-known/acme-challenge/test-file
- Public internet check:
	- curl -i http://<domain>/.well-known/acme-challenge/test-file
- Expected result: HTTP 200 with body "ok".
- If nginx access.log does not see the public request, the problem is before nginx.

8. Request the certificate
- Use the parent webroot, not the challenge directory itself:
	- sudo certbot certonly --webroot -w /var/www/certbot -d <domain>

9. TLS nginx phase
- Replace the bootstrap config with sendline-tls.conf.
- Validate nginx again:
	- sudo nginx -t
	- sudo systemctl reload nginx
- Verify both URLs:
	- curl -I http://<domain>/
	- curl -I https://<domain>/

10. App verification after HTTPS is live
- Direct app health check, bypassing nginx if possible:
	- curl -i http://127.0.0.1:8080/health
- Reverse-proxied health check:
	- curl -i https://<domain>/health
- If HTTPS returns 500 on the homepage, inspect app logs before touching nginx.

11. Logs to check
- nginx access log
- nginx error log
- app stdout/stderr
- docker logs <container> if the app runs in Docker
- journalctl -u <service-name> if the app runs as a systemd service

Common failure patterns:
- Connection timeout or no route to host:
	- OCI ingress, local firewall, or wrong public IP
- nginx access.log stays empty during a public curl:
	- packet never reached nginx
- HTTP challenge works locally but not publicly:
	- firewall or OCI rules
- HTTPS handshake works but homepage returns 500:
	- app-side error, often invalid env or an upstream exception
- Root page returns 500 immediately in this app:
	- first check PUBLIC_BASE_URL for a missing scheme or malformed value
